{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17606687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17606687"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:15:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:15:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15928"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15928"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8619"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63208"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8619"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15928"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48660"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8666"},{"type":"tags","id":"9595"},{"type":"tags","id":"10689"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20642"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20644"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63208"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early embryonic development, cells from different embryological origins contribute to the formation of the skull. The skull consists of the neurocranium (cranial vault) and viscerocranium (facial skeleton).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures develops primarily from neural crest cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Occipital bone","Parietal bone","Petrous temporal bone","Maxilla","Sphenoid bone"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe bones of the neurocranium have different embryological origins. The bones of the cranial vault (calvaria) develop through intramembranous ossification, while the bones of the cranial base develop through endochondral ossification.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emaxilla\u003C/strong\u003E develops primarily from neural crest cells as part of the viscerocranium (facial skeleton).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn contrast, the \u003Cstrong\u003Eoccipital bone\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eparietal bone\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Esphenoid bone\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Epetrous temporal bone\u003C/strong\u003E develop from paraxial mesoderm.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The neurocranium protects the brain and forms from both neural crest cells and paraxial mesoderm.","The viscerocranium forms the facial bones and develops primarily from neural crest cells."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48660"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15928"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48660"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T10:47:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T10:47:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8619"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63208"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCou